                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>In a letter of August 23, 1950, to Herschel V. Johnson, Ambassador of the United
                    States to Brazil, Mr. Miller stated in part that the Department had never been
                    enthusiastic about an oil loan to Mexico because of its possible effect on
                    United States relations with other countries to which we had denied petroleum
                    loans. Therefore the present loan proposal, which included as corollary Mexico’s
                    withdrawal of oil loan requests, appeared to be a desirable solution to the
                    problem despite the potential adverse effect on United States-Brazilian
                    relations of a credit to Mexico in the amount contemplated.</p>
                <p>For the text of this letter, see <ref target="#pg_760">page 760</ref>.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
